'''Aldermaston''' ({{pronEng|<U+02C8><U+0254><U+02D0>ld<U+0259>rm<U+0251><U+02D0>st<U+0259>n}}) is a rural village, [[Civil parishes in England|civil parish]] and [[Wards of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] in [[Berkshire]], [[South East England]], with a population of 927. The village is on the southern edge of the [[River Kennet]] [[flood plain]], near the [[Hampshire]] county boundary. It is equidistant from [[Newbury, Berkshire|Newbury]], [[Basingstoke]] and [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]] and {{convert|45|mi|km}} west of [[London]].

Aldermaston may have been inhabited as early as 1690 BC; a number of [[postholes]] &ndash; along with remains of cereal grains &ndash; have been found in the area. Written history of the village is traced back at least as far as the 9th century AD.  The [[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]s show that the [[Ealdorman]] of Berkshire had his country estate in the village.  The manor of Aldermaston was established by the early 11th century, when the village was given to the [[Achard]] family by [[Henry I of England|Henry I]]; the manor is documented in the [[Domesday survey]].  The [[Church of St Mary the Virgin, Aldermaston|village church]] was established in the 13th century, and some of the original [[Norman architecture]] remains in the building's structure.
The last resident Lord of the Manor, Charles Keyser, died in 1929.  The manor estate has been subsequently occupied by [[Associated Electrical Industries]], the [[United States Air Force]] [[XIX Tactical Air Command]], the [[Women's Land Army]], Collier Macmillan Schools, and [[Blue Circle Industries]].  The manor house is now run as a private corporate venue by the [[Compass Group]].

The name "Aldermaston" is synonymous with [[Nuclear weapons and the United Kingdom|the UK's nuclear weapons programme]], as well as the [[Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament]]. The [[Atomic Weapons Establishment]] (AWE), which develops, maintains, and disposes of the UK's nuclear weaponry is in the parish. Built on the site of the former [[RAF Aldermaston]], the plant has been the destination of numerous [[Aldermaston Marches]]. Until 2006, the village was home to the [[Aldermaston Pottery]], which was established by [[Alan Caiger-Smith]] and [[Geoffrey Eastop]] in 1955.

==History==
{{see also|Aldermaston Court#History of the estate}}

Evidence suggests that Aldermaston was inhabited in the 12th century BC, possibly extending back to 1690 BC.<ref name="Cunliffe 2005 37">{{harvtxt|Cunliffe|2005|p=37}}</ref>  [[Radiocarbon dating]] on a number of [[postholes]] and pits found in the area show activity from 1690&ndash;1390, 1319&ndash;1214, and 977&ndash;899 BC.  Remains of cereal grains &ndash; both wheat and barley &ndash; have been found in these excavations.  Tests show that the majority of the barley was [[Husk#Husking and dehulling|dehulled]], but that absence of such debris may mean that the cereal was brought in from other areas.<ref name="Cunliffe 2005 37" />

[[File:Aldermastonhouse.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A sketch of a large 17th-century country house|The 17th-century Aldermaston House, showing the building's proximity to the parish church]]

Before the [[Norman conquest of England]] in 1066 the land and properties of Aldermaston had formed part of the estates of England's foremost magnate, [[Harold Godwinson]], the [[Earl of Wessex]], who would later become [[King Harold II]] of England.<ref name="pageditchfield2" /> Harold's assessment of the village valued the village's 15 [[hide (unit)|hides]] at <U+00A3>20 a year.<ref name="pageditchfield2" /> As with much of the land seized by [[William the Conqueror]] after his arrival in England in 1066, Aldermaston was held in [[demesne]].<ref name="pageditchfield2" />  His [[Domesday Survey]] of 1086 identified the existence of a mill, worth twenty shillings, and two fisheries, worth five shillings.<ref name="Timmins 2000 6">{{harvtxt|Timmins|2000|p=6}}</ref> During the remainder of the reign of William, and later his son [[William Rufus]], Aldermaston was owned by the Crown. There is no evidence of there being a large house at that time.

The history of the [[Lords of the Manor]] of [[Aldermaston Court]] can be traced to Achard D'Aldermaston, who was born in 1036.<ref>{{harvtxt|Ford|2001}}</ref> Six families have had lordship of the Aldermaston estate.  In the 11th century, [[Henry I of England|Henry I]] gave to Robert Achard (or Hachard<ref name="National Archives 1290">{{harvtxt|National Archives|1290}}</ref>) of [[Sparsholt, Oxfordshire|Sparsholt]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Camden|1610|p=63}}</ref><ref name="The Topographer 1789 33">{{harvtxt|Topographer, The|1789|p=33}}</ref> In the mid-12th century, the Achard family founded the church of St Mary the Virgin.<ref name="Campbell 1982 1">{{harvtxt|Campbell|1982|p=1}}</ref>  In 1292, [[Edward I]] granted the right for the lord of the manor to hold a market in the village. Another charter was granted by [[Henry IV of England|Henry IV]], with evidence that the market existed until approximately 1900.<ref name="pageditchfield2" /> The Achards also established an annual fair to observe the feast of [[Thomas More|St. Thomas the Martyr]] on 7 July.<ref name="pageditchfield2" />

Aldermaston was held by the [[Aldermaston Court#The Achard Family (11th century <U+2013> 1361)|Achard family]] until the 14th century, when it passed through marriage to Thomas De La Mare of [[Nunney Castle]], [[Somerset]].<ref name="The Topographer 1789 33" /><ref name="Timmins 2000 7">{{harvtxt|Timmins|2000|p=7}}</ref> The [[Aldermaston Court#The De la Mare Family (1361<U+2013>1490)|De La Mare family]] governed Aldermaston for approximately 120 years, until Elizabeth de la Mare &ndash; whose male relatives predeceased her &ndash; married into the Forster family.<ref name="Timmins 2000 7"/> In about 1636, the Forsters built a large [[manor house]] to the east of the church. The house was fronted by two porches, separated by a central section with seven [[Bay (architecture)|bays]].<ref name="Mowl Earnshaw 1995 63">{{harvtxt|Mowl|Earnshaw|1995|p=63}}</ref>  The porches had ornate [[Solomonic column]]s, similar to those at the [[University Church of St Mary the Virgin]] in Oxford.<ref name="Mowl Earnshaw 1995 63" />  The interior of the house featured a number of mythical statues,<ref name="Piozzi Bloom Bloom 1996 208">{{harvtxt|Piozzi|Bloom|Bloom|1996|p=208}}</ref> as well as artwork by [[Gaspard Dughet]], portraits of [[William Congreve]] and [[Godfrey Kneller]], and [[Tintoretto]]'s ''[[Esther]] Before [[Ahasuerus]]''.<ref name="Knight 1840 104">{{harvtxt|Knight|1840|p=104}}</ref>  The house's [[Jacobean era|Jacobean]] garden featured patterns of groves and avenues of [[oak]], [[Taxus baccata|yew]], [[Spanish chestnut]] and [[lime tree]]s.<ref name="Martin 2005 65">{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=65}}</ref> In the early 18th century the Forsters oversaw the building of [[almshouse]]s in Church Road. Built by R Dixon in 1706, the houses became known as "Dixon's Cottages". The manor passed through the [[Aldermaston Court#The Forster Family (1490 - 1752)|Forster family]] until 1752, when the Forster lineage ended and the estate was inherited by [[Aldermaston Court#The Congreve family (1752 - 1843)|Ralph Congreve]] &ndash; the husband of the last Forster's grand-niece.

[[File:Aldermaston Manor.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A photograph of a grand Victorian manor house|[[Aldermaston Manor]] was built in the 1840s]]
On Ralph's death a second-cousin of dramatist [[William Congreve]] inherited the manor.<ref name="Wilson 1896">{{harvtxt|Wilson|1896}}</ref> The Congreve Family owned the estate at the time of the 1830 [[Swing Riot]]s. The rioters marched across Aldermaston, wrecking twenty-three agricultural machines. Workers were so frightened by the riots that they left their machinery in the open in an attempt to limit additional damage.<ref name="Ford 2005"/> Around the same time, the River Kennet (along the north side of the estate) was made navigable between Reading and Newbury.<ref>{{harvtxt|Kennet and Avon Canal Trust|2010}}</ref>

In 1843, the manor house was destroyed by fire, news of which was carried in ''[[The Illustrated London News]]''.<ref name="Campbell 1982 1"/> The estate passed into the [[Court of Chancery]] and was purchased by [[Aldermaston Court#The Burr family (1849 - 1893)|Daniel Burr]].  In 1848, Burr commissioned the building of a neoclassical mansion to the south west of the original building.  Burr saved the 17th-century manor's wooden staircase, though all that remains of the building is a staircase to the cellar (which is now home to a colony of [[bat]]s).<ref name="Martin 2005 65"/> By 1851 the new building was complete, costing <U+00A3>20,000 and having a Tudor-like appearance.<ref>{{harvtxt|Pevsner|1966|p=45}}</ref> Burr held the estate until his death 50 years later, when was inherited by his son, who sold it in 1893.

[[File:NashAldermaston.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A monochrome lithograph of a grand wooden stair case|[[Joseph Nash]]'s 1849 lithograph of the staircase at Aldermaston Manor]]
The buyer was wealthy [[stockbroker]] [[Aldermaston Court#The Keyser family (1893 - 1938)|Charles Edward Keyser]], who was preoccupied with the idea of keeping the village unchanged &ndash; or, as he described it &ndash; "unspoilt".<ref name="Timmins 2000 11">{{harvtxt|Timmins|2000|p=11}}</ref> He forbade advertisements, opposed all modernisation and refused to allow any expansion by the building of houses. He did, however, commission the building of a parish hall in 1897 and provided the village with a water supply,<ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2007 1">{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2007|p=1}}</ref> and the water fountain on the small village green was installed to commemorate [[Victoria of the United Kingdom#Diamond Jubilee|Queen Victoria's Diamond Jubilee]]. Keyser oversaw the restoration of the village almshouses in 1906 and 1924, and defrayed the cost of a memorial oak tablet in memory of those killed in [[World War I]]. Of the 100 men from the village that served in [[World War I]], 22 were killed (the highest percentage of town population in the country). The tablet bears the name of each man lost in action.<ref name="Cox 1977 4">{{harvtxt|Cox|1977|p=4}}</ref> 

During Keyser's lordship, John Marius Wilson's ''[[Imperial Gazetteer of England and Wales]]'' listed ''Adminston'' as a possible name for the village.<ref name="Wilson 1896"/>   On his death in 1929, his wife, Mary, continued to occupy the house until she died in 1938.  The estate was auctioned off in September 1938, with many lots being purchased by their occupiers.  The manor house was bought by [[Associated Electrical Industries]] (AEI) for <U+00A3>16,000.<ref>{{harvtxt|Scott|2007|p=1}}</ref> One of the houses in the village is recorded as having fetched <U+00A3>1,375.<ref>{{harvtxt|Campbell|1982|p=2}}.</ref> As AEI's chairman, [[Felix Pole]] became the ''[[de jure]]'' Lord of the Manor upon their purchase of Aldermaston Court.<ref name="Timmins 2000 12">{{harvtxt|Timmins|2000|p=12}}</ref>

During the 1940s [[RAF Aldermaston]] was created on the parkland at the southern end of the parish, with [[XIX Tactical Air Command]] stationed at the manor house.<ref>{{harvtxt|Timmins|2000|p=14}}</ref> After [[World War II]], the manor was returned to AEI who built the [[MERLIN reactor]] on part of the land. The reactor was opened on 6 November 1959 by [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=25}}</ref> With the opening of the [[Atomic Weapons Research Establishment]] (AWRE) in 1950, Aldermaston became synonymous with a number of [[Aldermaston Marches|CND marches]].<ref name="BBC News 2007">{{harvtxt|BBC News|2007}}</ref>

In 1953, Pole stepped down as Lord of the Manor and was succeeded by AEI's senior representative, [[Thomas Allibone]]. Allibone held the position for 32 years, until [[Blue Circle Industries]] acquired the estate in 1985.<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2007a|p=15}}</ref> Allibone was succeeded by Tony Jackson.<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=63}}</ref> Blue Circle could not gain [[planning permission]] in the grounds of the court, so the MERLIN reactor was demolished to make way for [[Portland House, Aldermaston|Portland House]].  With a full redevelopment of Aldermaston Manor, the <U+00A3>14 million office development &ndash; which would be Blue Circle's international headquarters &ndash; was opened by [[Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=66}}</ref>

=== Toponymy ===
The village of Aldermaston derives its name from ''<U+00C6>ldremanestone'', ''Eldremanestune'' or ''Hedlremanestone'', the [[Old English]] for "Ealdorman's Homestead".<ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2007a 1">{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2007a|p=1}}</ref> The [[Ealdorman]] &ndash; or [[Alderman]] &ndash; was a person of extreme importance, equating to the modern-day [[Lord-Lieutenant]] of the County. Although his country estate was in Aldermaston, he would have spent most of the time in the original county town of [[Wallingford, Oxfordshire|Wallingford]].<ref name="Ford 2005">{{harvtxt|Ford|2005}}</ref> The [[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]] states that the first known Ealdorman of Berkshire, Aethelwulf, fought the [[Danes (Germanic tribe)|Danes]] with [[Ethelred of Wessex]] at nearby [[Englefield, Berkshire|Englefield]] in 871.

Other documented names include Aldermaston ad Pontem (11th century),<ref name="pageditchfield2">{{harvtxt|Page|Ditchfield|1923|p=2}}</ref> Aldremanneston (12th century),<ref name="Gelling 1973 198">{{harvtxt|Gelling|1973|p=198}}</ref> Aldremaneston (13th century),<ref name="Gelling 1973 198" /> Aldermanston (14th century),<ref name="National Archives 1339">{{harvtxt|National Archives|1339}}</ref> and Aldmerston (19th century).<ref name="Lewis 1835 49">{{harvtxt|Lewis|1835|p=49}}</ref>

==Governance==
Historically, Aldermaston was a [[Hundred (county subdivision)#England|hundred]], though for a period it was within the Theale hundred.<ref name="Youngs 1979 14">{{harvtxt|Youngs|1979|p=14}}</ref> By the 19th century, the hundreds had been superseded by other sub-divisions.  From then on, Aldermaston was, at times, part of the [[Bradfield, Berkshire|Bradfield]] [[Poor Law Union]] and [[Sanitary District]], and the registration sub-districts of Mortimer (late 19th century) and Bucklebury (early 20th century).<ref name="Youngs 1979 14"/> It was later an [[Parish#Ecclesiastical parish|ecclesiastical parish]].<ref name="Youngs 1979 14"/>

Aldermaston is now a civil parish with an elected parish council. It is in the area of [[West Berkshire]] [[Unitary authorities of England|unitary authority]]. The [[Wards of the United Kingdom|electoral ward]] of Aldermaston includes the neighbouring parishes of [[Wasing]], [[Brimpton]], [[Midgham]], and [[Woolhampton]].<ref name="ReferenceA">{{harvtxt|Office of National Statistics|2010a}}</ref> The ward is the smallest in [[West Berkshire]] by population.<ref>{{harvtxt|West Berkshire Council|2007a}}</ref> The ward's [[councillor]] is Irene Neill, who represents the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]].<ref>{{harvtxt|West Berkshire Council|2010b}}</ref>

Aldermaston is under the catchment of [[Thames Valley Police]] and is covered by the Brimpton Neighbourhood Policing Team.<ref>{{harvtxt|West Berkshire Council|2010a}}</ref> In a meeting with Aldermaston Parish Council, the police reported that 57 criminal offences were reported to have taken place in the parish between 2009 and 2010.<ref name="Newbury Today 2010">{{harvtxt|Newbury Today|2010}}</ref> Of this, the majority was theft from non-dwelling properties. Vehicle crime had dropped by 57% on the previous year but [[violent crime]] had risen from four to six incidents. Five of these crimes were reported to be [[domestic violence]].  There have been no reported cases of [[robbery]] in Aldermaston since 2006.<ref name="Newbury Today 2010"/>

==Geography==
[[File:AldermastonLoosey.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph of a small village green, showing a drinking fountain, oak tree, and well|The Loosey with the fountain (left) and well (to the right of the oak tree) visible]]
Aldermaston is in West Berkshire, about {{convert|2|mi|km}} from the Hampshire boundary. The village is {{convert|1|mi|km}} south of the [[A4 road (Great Britain)|A4 road]] that links the parish with Newbury and Reading. The main road in Aldermaston, The Street, is part of the [[A340 road]] and links the village with [[Pangbourne]] and Basingstoke. The course of [[Ermin Street]], the [[Roman road]] that linked [[Calleva Atrebatum]] ([[Silchester]]) with [[Glevum]] ([[Gloucester]]) ''via'' [[Corinium Dobunnorum]] ([[Cirencester]]) runs south of the village, but none of the road survives in the area.<ref>{{harvtxt|Streetmap|2010}}</ref>

At the southern end of The Street is a small triangular [[village green]] called The Loosey. The Loosey is the site of a Roman well, discovered in 1940 by a cow that almost fell down it.<ref name="Timmins 2000 11"/> The Loosey was previously home to the village [[maypole]] (which was often climbed by Daniel Burr's monkey) and a drinking fountain erected by Charles Keyser to celebrate the [[Victoria of the United Kingdom#Diamond Jubilee|Diamond Jubilee of Queen Victoria]].<ref name="Timmins 2000 11"/> Although no longer in use, the drinking fountain remains intact on the Loosey.

The [[River Kennet]] and [[River Enborne]] flow through the parish.  The confluence of the rivers is approximately {{convert|0.6|mi|km}} north of the village.<ref name="floodreport3">{{harvtxt|West Berkshire Council|2007b|p=3}}</ref>  The [[Kennet and Avon Canal]] forms part of the parish's boundaries with [[Woolhampton]] and [[Padworth]].

Sections of [[Grim's Bank]] are in the parish. Part of the earthwork in the AWE complex survives at a height of {{convert|3.3|m|ft}} and with a ditch {{convert|0.9|m|ft}} deep.<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2007b}}</ref>

===Geology===
The landscape of Aldermaston is influenced by Paices Hill and Rag Hill, which are extremities of the chalk formation the [[North Wessex Downs]] as part of the Thames Basin Heaths.<ref>{{harvtxt|North Wessex Downs AONB|2010}}</ref><ref>{{harvtxt|Joint Nature Conservation Committee|2010}}</ref>  The topography of the land in the parish generally slopes northward to the River Kennet.<ref name="floodreport3" />

===Flooding===
{{see also|2007 United Kingdom floods}}
[[File:AldermastonFloodGrilles.jpg|thumb|left|alt=Photograph of a wall with 17 semi-circular grilles built into it. The grilles are spaced horizontally along the wall's length|The flood grilles on Church Road (the rebuilt section of the wall is clearly contrasted against the older sections)]]
The geology and location of Aldermaston has resulted in severe flooding on three occasions &ndash; 1971, 1989, and 2007.<ref name="Newbury Today 2008">{{harvtxt|Newbury Today|2008}}</ref><ref name="Martin 2005 85">{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=85}}</ref> The flood in 1971 was caused by torrential rain flooding the [[balancing pond]]s [[Atomic Weapons Establishment]], which were unable to cope with the rainfall.<ref name="Martin 2005 85"/> This happened again in July 1989, when {{convert|6|in|mm}} of rain was deposited on the village in two hours.  Five feet of water built up from the ponds, and broke through a brick wall, flooding the village. The destroyed wall was rebuilt with 17 grilles to avoid another build-up of water.<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=88}}</ref> A donation of <U+00A3>10,000 was given to the village by [[Blue Circle]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=89}}</ref>

In July 2007, torrential rain flooded the village and local primary school, with the event making national news.<ref name="harvtxt|Newbury Today|2007a">{{harvtxt|Newbury Today|2007a}}</ref> The storm coincided with the annual [[The Glade|Glade music festival]] and jeopardised the event.<ref>{{harvtxt|Newbury Today|2007b}}</ref> The festival gates were temporarily closed while organisers assessed the flooding, which submerged one of the stages.<ref name="Virtual Festivals 2007">{{harvtxt|Virtual Festivals|2007}}</ref> The festival's car park was incapacitated, with thousands of revellers stranded in the village and surrounding lanes.<ref>{{harvtxt|BBC Berkshire|2007b}}</ref>

[[File:2007 Aldermaston Flooding.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph showing severe flooding to a road and housing; cars are partly submerged and fire appliances (including a dinghy) are in the distance|The flooding affected the lower end of The Street]]
The floods also hit the Church of England primary school, with the [[Royal Berkshire Fire and Rescue Service]] evacuating pupils and staff from the school in [[life raft]]s.<ref name="BBC News 2007"/><ref>{{harvtxt|Independent, The|2007}}</ref> The evacuation used four rafts, rescuing pupils and teachers from the school through windows.<ref>{{harvtxt|White|2007}}</ref> The 165 people (140 pupils and 25 members of staff) were taken uphill to the parish hall, where blankets and sleeping bags had been provided.<ref name="harvtxt|Newbury Today|2007a"/>

Ian Henderson, a [[police constable]] at [[Thames Valley Police]] stated that the emergency services were "really stretched because of what happened over the county and the Glade event", that "the [A340] junction was two or three foot under water", and predicted that "a lot of householders [would be] homeless."<ref name="harvtxt|Newbury Today|2007a"/>

==Demography==
The 1831 census showed that 68% of the employed population of Aldermaston were [[working class]] or "labourers and servants".<ref name="GBHS 2010d">{{harvtxt|Great Britain Historical GIS|2010d}}</ref> 20% were [[middle class]] ("middling sorts"), 10% were [[upper class]] ("employers and professionals") and 2% were unclassified.<ref name="GBHS 2010d" />

In 1887 the population of the parish was 528.<ref>{{harvtxt|Bartholomew|1887}}</ref> By 1896, the population had grown to 585.<ref name="Wilson 1896"/>  The population fluctuated steadily around 550 until the 1950s and 1960s, when a [[population explosion]] resulted in the 1961 UK census reporting 2,186 residents in the parish.<ref name="GBHS 2010a">{{harvtxt|Great Britain Historical GIS|2010a}}</ref> This coincides with the opening of the Atomic Weapons Establishment in the early 1950s, and the majority of this figure counts residents in the parts of [[Tadley]] within the parish of Aldermaston<ref name="Timmins 2000 15">{{harvtxt|Timmins|2000|p=15}}</ref> &ndash; between 1901 and 1961, 368 houses were built in the parish.<ref name="GBHS 2010e">{{harvtxt|Great Britain Historical GIS|2010e}}</ref>

[[File:Aldermaston population nokey.svg|thumb|alt=A pie chart showing 2005 population distribution in the parish of Aldermaston|{{Talk:Aldermaston/Population_key}}]]
A number of parish border changes occurred in the first half of the 20th century, including the net loss of {{convert|307|acre|ha}} to Beenham and Woolhampton on 1 April 1934 alone.<ref>{{harvtxt|Great Britain Historical GIS|2010b}}</ref> By 2001, the parish population had reduced to 927.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>

The [[2001 United Kingdom Census]] identified that 99.3% of householders in the parish as [[White people|white]].<ref name="ReferenceB">{{harvtxt|Office of National Statistics|2010b}}</ref> In 2005 30% of parish residents lived in the village.<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2006|p=22}}</ref> Of the 70% outside the village, 30% lived at Aldermaston Wharf, 20% in the local mobile home parks, 10% in the Falcon Fields development and 10% in "other outlying areas".<ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2006 10">{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2006|p=10}}</ref> Falcon Fields is a housing development on the southern border of the parish, completed in the early 2000s. Ravenswing and Pinelands are [[mobile home]] parks near the Hampshire border.<ref>{{harvtxt|Park Home Living|2010a}}</ref><ref>{{harvtxt|Park Home Living|2010b}}</ref> Raghill is a industrial area to the east of the parish, which has some light residential developments.

The average age of residents in the parish is approximately 50 with 31.5% of residents in the 45<U+2013>64 age group.<ref name="ReferenceB"/> The average age of residents of Aldermaston Wharf is 30.7, and in the mobile home parks the average age is 53.9.<ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2006 10"/> Of these, 53.3% were female.<ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2006 10"/> This is in contrast with the 2001 census data, which showed that 49.8% were female.<ref name="ReferenceB"/>

In 2005, 3% of the parish population were unemployed and 25% were retired.<ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2006 10"/>  The retirement figure increased in the Pinelands and Ravenswing areas, with a statistic of 42%.<ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2006 10"/> Most residents' places of work are in surrounding towns, with their location in the parish largely dictating where to look for work &ndash; the 2005 survey identified that residents in the south of the parish (Falcon Fields and Ravenswing/Pinelands) travel towards Tadley and Basingstoke whereas those further north in the parish tend to find work in Reading, Newbury and London.<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2006|p=11}}</ref>

