==Economy==
Historically, the main source of industry in Aldermaston has been agriculture.  According to the 1831 census, approximately 66% of working men (aged 20 and over) were employed in some form of agriculture.<ref name="GBHS 2010c">{{harvtxt|Great Britain Historical GIS|2010c}}</ref> The next highest industry by workers was "retail and handicrafts", which employed approximately 20%.<ref name="GBHS 2010c" /> Employment categories in the 1881 census were more discreet; just 20% of working men identified their employment as agriculture.  30% however, were listed as "general or unspecified commodities".<ref name="GBHS 2010c" />  In this census, women's employment was also documented.  Of the 137 working women in the parish, 40 (slightly fewer than 30%) worked in domestic services, whereas 82 (approximately 60%) were of an unknown occupation.<ref name="GBHS 2010c" />

===Agriculture===
In about 1797<ref name="Martin 2005 3">{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=3}}</ref> a schoolmaster living in the village cultivated the [[Williams pear]]. The schoolmaster &ndash; either Mr Wheeler<ref name="Martin 2005 3"/> or his successor, John Stair<ref>{{harvtxt|USA Pears|2009}}</ref> &ndash; was the original cultivator, but the pear (a [[cultivar]] of the [[European Pear]]) was named after Richard Williams of [[Turnham Green]], who grew several grafts of the original tree.<ref name="Martin 2005 3"/> On 5 December 1956, a plaque commemorating the tree was unveiled on the wall of the village school.<ref name="Martin 2005 3"/>

Locally-farmed wheat was milled at Aldermaston Mill until the 1920s.<ref>{{harvtxt|Cox|1977|p=6}}</ref> In existence at the time of the Domesday survey, the mill was previously called the "Kingsmill", and at one time supplied [[flour]] to [[Huntley & Palmers]] in Reading.<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=53}}</ref> Now known as The Old Mill, it was owned by Wasing's Mount family throughout the 18th and 19th centuries.  William Mount let the mill to Francis Webb (1797<U+2013>1811), Mr Sherwood (1811<U+2013>1820), Mr King (1820<U+2013>1824), Mr Waldren (1824<U+2013>1828), Mr Mathews (1828<U+2013>1848), and William Gilchrist (1848<U+2013>1856).<ref name="Mill1">{{harvtxt|Old Mill, The|2010|p=1}}</ref>  Gilchrist (Mathews' business partner) bought the mill from Mount in 1856 using money inherited from his brother's death the previous year.<ref name="Mill2">{{harvtxt|Old Mill, The|2010|p=2}}</ref> Owning it outright for approximately a year, he drowned in the River Kennet in 1857 after visiting the Angel public house in Woolhampton.<ref name="Mill2" /> Joseph Crockett purchased the mill in an auction the same year, before it was acquired by a  Richard Sisling of [[Godalming]] in 1858.  In approximately 1860, the mill was purchased by the Kersley family.  Between then and 1885, it was operated by Anthony Kersley, a miller and [[malster]] who employed "six men and a boy, a carter, several domestic servants and a governess".<ref name="Mill2" />  Kersley's son, also named Anthony, ran the mill until 1895.  That year, Walter Parson bought the mill and operated it until approximately 1897.  Charles Keyser subsequently oversaw restoration on the mill building which "had been untenanted for upwards of three years".  He let the mill out to a Mr Iremonger from 1901.  Iremonger used the mill until the late 1920s, shortly before Keyser's death.<ref name="Mill2" />  After Keyser had died and the Aldermaston estate had been divided and sold, his widow, Mary, approached Evelyn Arlott to run the mill as a [[tea room]] and [[guesthouse]].  The Arlott family purchased the mill in approximately 1939, after the death of Mary Keyser.<ref name="Mill5">{{harvtxt|Old Mill, The|2010|p=5}}</ref>

In 1939, there were seven farms on the Aldermaston estate &ndash; Forsters Farm, Village Farm, Church Farm, Upper Church Farm, Raghill Farm, Park Farm, and Soke Farm. These accounted for approximately 75% of the estate's land.<ref name="Scott 2007 6">{{harvtxt|Scott|2007|p=6}}</ref> Aside from these, there were six [[smallholding]]s within the parish but outside the land owned by the court. These were Springhill Farm, Court Farm, Strawberry Farm, Circus Farm, Ravenswing Farm, and Frouds Farm.<ref name="Scott 2007 6"/>

Of these, only two farms remain in operation &ndash; Church Farm and Forster's Farm.<ref>{{harvtxt|Bucknell|1965}}</ref> Upper Church Farm was originally known as Harry's Farm, after a William Harry who died in 1544.<ref>{{harvtxt|Cox|1977|p=12}}</ref>

===Pubs and brewing===
The local [[pub]] is named The Hind's Head in honour of the Forster family crest. Built in the 17th century and originally operating as a [[coaching inn]],<ref name="Reader's Digest Association 1990 18">{{harvtxt|Reader's Digest Association|1990|p=18}}</ref> the establishment was named The Pack Horse during the De La Mare and Forster lordships and The Congreve Arms throughout the Congreves' ownership.<ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2007 3">{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2007|p=3}}</ref><ref>{{harvtxt|Ingram|Ingram|Ridley|1976|p=48}}</ref>
[[File:HindsHead.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A photograph of a public house|The Hind's Head Inn]]
The building has a large black and gold clock set into the [[gable]], and a small bellturret upon which is a [[Gilding|gilt]] fox-shaped [[weather vane]].<ref name="Reader's Digest Association 1990 18"/> The bell was intended to be rung as an [[Civil defense siren|air-raid siren]] during the Second World War.<ref name="Ingram 1976 49">{{harvtxt|Ingram|Ingram|Ridley|1976|p=49}}</ref> In the early 19th century the pub's [[signboard]] carried the arms of the Congreve family, as well as branding for a company named "Adams". In the ''British Parliamentary Papers'' of 1817, the Committee on the State of the Police in the Metropolis reported evidence of a John Adams &ndash; a Reading-based [[distiller]] and [[hops|hop merchant]], who competed for business against [[Simonds' Brewery]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Corley|1976|p=79}}</ref> By 1850, the pub brewed beer on-site; a brewery was built as an out-building behind the main pub building. John Knight produced beer at the pub for 40 years, selling it for [[Penny (British pre-decimal coin)|2d]]. The brewery building is still in existence, with the wooden [[Louver|louvres]] still operational.<ref name="Ingram 1976 49"/> The building is now the pub's kitchen. In the 1970s, the pub was owned by [[Whitbread]].<ref name="Ingram 1976 49"/><ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=43}}</ref> In the mid-1990s the pub was taken over by [[Gales Brewery]] (having previously been a [[Free house (pub)|free house]]), later becoming tied to [[Fuller's Brewery]] on their acquisition of Gales in 2006.<ref>{{harvtxt|Klinger|2005}}</ref><ref>{{harvtxt|Portsmouth Today|2006}}</ref> In the 1970s, the pub was home to the Kennet Folk Club.<ref name="Ingram 1976 49"/>

The pub has its own gaol-house, the lock-up, at the rear. Built out of red brick, the small single-storey building has a shallow domed roof.  The inside of the lock-up measures approximately {{convert|7.5|ft|m}} by {{convert|6|ft|m}}, and is enclosed by a studded door with a grille.<ref name="hod_lockup">{{harvtxt|Heritage Open Days|2010a}}</ref>  It was last used in 1865 and its drunk inhabitant burnt himself to death trying to keep warm.<ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2007 3"/><ref>{{harvtxt|Campbell|1982|p=2}}</ref> The lock-up was designated as a [[Grade II]] listed building in April 1967.<ref>{{harvtxt|Images of England|2007a}}</ref> On 11 September 2010 the lock-up was opened to the public as part of the [[Heritage Open Days]] scheme.<ref name="hod_lockup" />

Another pub in the parish, The Butt Inn, is located approximately {{convert|1.25|mi|km}} north-east of the village.<ref>{{harvtxt|Waterscape|2010a}}</ref> The pub is named after the [[archery butts]] that were located in the fields opposite the pub.<ref name="Wordsworth Reference 2006 68">{{harvtxt|Wordsworth Reference|2006|p=68}}</ref>

The [[Aldermaston Brewery]] was established at [[Aldermaston Wharf]] in 1770, and was demolished in the 1950s.<ref>{{harvtxt|Berkshire Record Office|2010}}</ref> It was replaced with a cable factory, which was demolished in 1990.<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=114}}</ref>

===Cricket bats===
Old Village Farm (on Fishermans Lane) is now the location of a wood yard, used since the 1930s to prepare local [[willow]] for the production of [[cricket bat]]s.<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2006|p=5}}</ref> The trees are grown at Harbour Hill Copse,<ref name="ReferenceC">{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2010b}}</ref> where 70 trees are felled annually for this purpose.  There are approximately 1000 trees growing at any given time.<ref>{{harvtxt|Padworth Parish Council|2010}}</ref> The workers at the yard cut the wood into approximate bat shaps, then cure the wood in a kiln.  The clefts of wood are then shipped to [[India]] where the final manufacturing can be undertaken under moisture-controlled conditions.<ref name="ReferenceC"/>

The yard would take on three up-coming cricketers for the winter, in the hope that the hard work would "toughen them up" to get them picked for the [[England cricket team]]. One year the yard had help from [[Frank Tyson]], [[Alan Moss]], and [[Peter Loader]]. The following year they hosted three Davids &ndash; David Kaufman, David Spragbury, and [[David Gibson (cricketer)|David Gibson]].<ref name="Martin 2005 38">{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=38}}</ref>

The wood yard was featured on ''[[A Question of Sport]]'', when cricketer [[Graham Gooch]] took part in the programme's "Mystery Guest" round.<ref name="Martin 2005 50">{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=50}}</ref> Gooch endorsed the bats made from Aldermaston willow, which were sold by [[Surridge]]. When he scored 333 runs against India at [[Lord's]] in the 1990 [[Test cricket|test season]], the Turbo 333 bat, made from Aldermaston wood, was launched in his honour.<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=92}}</ref>

In the 1960s, ''[[Blue Peter]]'' aired a short documentary on the cricket bat production entitled "The Life of a Cricket Bat".  It was presented by [[Christopher Trace]].<ref name="Martin 2005 38"/>

===Pottery===
In 1955, the [[Aldermaston Pottery]] was established on the main street<ref name="Studio Pottery 2006">{{harvtxt|Studio Pottery|2006}}</ref> by [[studio potter]]s [[Alan Caiger-Smith]] and [[Geoffrey Eastop]].<ref name="Studio Pottery 2006"/> The pottery was renowned for [[Tin-glazed pottery|tin-glazed]] and [[porcelain]] wares,<ref name="Studio Pottery 2006"/>  which used scrap wood from the Village Farm woodyard to fire the kiln.<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=36}}</ref>
The pottery closed in 2006.<ref>{{harvtxt|Ceramic Review|2006}}</ref> It had previously scaled back its output in 1993 due to Caiger-Smith's partial retirement after the [[Early 1990s recession|1992 recession]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=116}}</ref>

===Other businesses===
[[File:AWE.jpg|thumb|alt=Aerial photograph showing a large industrial area, including a number of laboratory buildings (some with chimneys), roadways, and recreational areas|Aerial view of [[Atomic Weapons Establishment|AWE]]]]
The [[Atomic Weapons Establishment]] (AWE), for which Aldermaston has become known,<ref name="BBC News 2000">{{harvtxt|BBC News|2000}}</ref> is less than {{convert|1|mi|km}} south of the village. In April 1958, the first [[Aldermaston March]] was held.<ref name="Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament 2008">{{harvtxt|Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament|2008}}</ref> The march saw around 3,000 protesters march from London to Aldermaston over four days, with a total attendance of 12,000 at the establishment's gates.<ref name="Campaign for Nuclear Disarmament 2008"/> The 50th anniversary of the event was marked on 24 March 2008 with the "Bomb Stops Here" protest, attended by [[Vivienne Westwood]] and [[CND]] president [[Walter Wolfgang]].<ref>{{harvtxt|BBC News|2008}}</ref><ref>{{harvtxt|Guardian, The|2008}}</ref> The 2008 demonstration was the biggest protest staged by CND in ten years.<ref>{{harvtxt|Barnett|2008}}</ref>
Until 2005, AWE discharged "pre-treated waste water"<ref name="AWE 2011">{{harvtxt|AWE|2011}}</ref> into the River Thames at [[Pangbourne]] via an {{convert|11.8|mi|km}} pipeline which runs under roads and fields within the parish.<ref name="Nuclear Information Service 2003">{{harvtxt|Nuclear Information Service|2003}}</ref> A water processing facility was installed on-site in 2006, though the Pangbourne Pipeline remains ''in situ''.<ref name="AWE 2011" />

[[Lafarge Aggregates]] owns varios sites in the parish. In 1974 the village won an appeal against [[Pioneer Concrete]]'s application for [[gravel extraction]] near the village.<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=46}}</ref> Similar events took place in March 2003 when hundreds of local residents protested against an application of gravel extraction by Lafarge.<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=188}}</ref> Larfarge's initial appeal, in April 2003, was turned down by [[West Berkshire Council]]. A further application to extract aggregate at the [[Wasing Estate]] is due to be decided in 2010.<ref name="Newbury Today 2008"/> One former extraction site, [[Butts Lake Quarry]], is now a nature reserve and the flooded lakes have been identified as a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] and is now operated by the [[Berkshire, Buckinghamshire and Oxfordshire Wildlife Trust]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2005}}</ref> The reserve contains specimens of trees such as [[alder]], [[cherry tree|cherry]], [[Crataegus monogyna|hawthorn]], [[oak]], and [[willow]].  Examples of [[Reed (plant)|reed]]s present include ''[[typha latifolia]]'', ''[[phragmites australis]]'', ''[[mentha aquatica]]'', and ''[[lythrum salicaria]]''.  Numerous species of bird nest in the reserve, including the [[common teal]], [[shoveler]], [[warbler]], [[kingfisher]], [[water rail]], and [[nightingale]].<ref>{{harvtxt|English Nature|2006|p=1}}</ref>

[[File:Aldermaston Petrol.png|thumb|left|alt=A black-and-white photograph showing an old car in a wooden roadside petrol station. A man in uniform is standing next to the station's single small building|The [[The Automobile Association|AA]]'s first roadside petrol station on the Bath Road near Aldermaston. The road bridge near [[Aldermaston railway station]] can be seen in the background]]

[[The Automobile Association|The AA]] opened its first roadside [[petrol filling station]] on the [[Bath Road]] near Aldermaston on 2 March 1919.<ref>{{harvtxt|Jeremiah|1995|p=100}}</ref><ref>{{harvtxt|Baker|2008}}</ref> The following year, one villager requested that a pump be installed by his house. "Chuffer" Ford, who lived in The Forge with his wife Olive,<ref name="Martin 2005 13">{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=13}}</ref> was told by Keyser that it must be "behind a wall and recessed".<ref>{{harvtxt|Bond|2008}}</ref> A hole was cut in the brick wall beside Ford's yard to house the [[Royal Dutch Shell|Shell]]-branded pump.<ref name="Martin 2005 13"/> The location of this pump is marked by a square hole in the present wall. Ford's business offered other motoring services, with signage reading "[[vacuum]], [[motor oil|oil]], and [[bicycle|cycles]]".<ref>{{harvtxt|Hill|1971|p=156}}</ref>

There is a number of small businesses in the village, including a [[hairdressing salon]], a [[software development]] company and the [[village shop]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2010c}}</ref>  In the 1970s the hairdressers was a music shop, which was opened by [[Terry Wogan]].<ref name="Martin 2005 56">{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=56}}</ref> Before this it was a [[cooperative]] village stores started by Charles Keyser.<ref name="Martin 2005 56"/>

There are two [[business park]]s in the parish &ndash; Calleva Business Park (on the Berkshire/Hampshire border)<ref>{{harvtxt|Calleva Park|2008}}</ref> and Youngs Industrial Estate (on Paices Hill).<ref>{{harvtxt|Youngs Industrial Estate|2008}}</ref> The latter opened in the early 1980s, and is the location of Paices Wood Country Parkland, a wildlife project sponsored by [[English Nature]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Paices Wood Country Parkland|2009}}</ref>

In 2007 Aldermaston won the Business Category Award in the regional final of the [[Calor Village of the Year]] competition. The judges stated that the village "has a very successful business community" and that "local businesses are well-supported by villagers and in return these businesses support village activities".<ref>{{harvtxt|Calor|2007}}</ref> In addition to the business award, the village was announced as the Overall Winner of the Calor "Berkshire Village of the Year" competition in 2006, as well as category winners in the "Building Community Life", "Business", "Young People" and "ICT" categories.<ref>{{harvtxt|Calor|2006}}</ref><ref>{{harvtxt|BBC Berkshire|2006}}</ref>

==Architecture==
The majority of houses in the village were built between the 17th and late 19th centuries, including examples of [[Victorian Gothic architecture]].<ref name="Reader's Digest Association 1990 18"/> Only one house has been built on the village's main street since the early 20th century.<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2007c}}</ref> The parish hall, built in 1897, is predominantly flint and brick.<ref name="Scott 2007 10">{{harvtxt|Scott|2007|p=10}}</ref>

Most of the houses in the village are Grade II listed buildings, and many were built using local red and blue bricks.<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2007a|p=3}}</ref> In total, 51 buildings in the parish are listed<ref>{{harvtxt|Images of England|2007b}}</ref> &ndash; including gatepiers,<ref>{{harvtxt|Images of England|2007c}}</ref> [[greenhouse]]s,<ref>{{harvtxt|Images of England|2007d}}</ref> a [[tomb]],<ref>{{harvtxt|Images of England|2007e}}</ref> [[Guard rail|railing]]s,<ref>{{harvtxt|Images of England|2007f}}</ref> and the village [[telephone box]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Images of England|2007g}}</ref>

==Culture==
Since the early 1800s, Aldermaston has held a [[candle auction]] every three years. The auction, which sees a horseshoe nail driven through a [[tallow]] candle an inch below the wick, is held in the parish hall.<ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2007 4">{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2007|p=4}}</ref> The lot is the lease of Church Acre,<ref name="Ford 2005"/> a plot {{convert|2|acre|ha}} in area that was granted to the church in 1815 after the [[Inclosures Act]].<ref name="Reader's Digest Association 1990 18"/><ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=4}}</ref> The proceedings are overseen by the vicar and churchwardens, who drink rum punch throughout the auction. Traditionally, the churchwardens smoked clay pipes during the event.<ref name="Reader's Digest Association 1990 18"/><ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2007 4"/>

The parish hall often holds other events, such as plays produced by the village's own [[amateur dramatics]] society. The society, known as The Aldermaston Players, have staged fundraising events in the village 1966.<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Players|2010}}</ref> In 1976, the parish hall hosted an episode of the BBC's ''[[Any Questions?]]''. The panel was chaired by [[David Jacobs (disc jockey)|David Jacobs]] and included [[Richard Marsh, Baron Marsh|Baron Marsh]], [[Katharine Whitehorn]], [[Beryl Reid]], and [[Colin James (bishop)|Colin James]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=48}}</ref>

The village, along with the neighbouring parish of Wasing, holds an annual [[f<U+00EA>te|produce show]] at The Old Mill.<ref name="Newbury Today 2009">{{harvtxt|Newbury Today|2009}}</ref> The show, which was previously held behind the Hind's Head pub,<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=35}}</ref> hosts produce competitions in approximately 100 classes.<ref name="Newbury Today 2009"/> In the 1990s, a team of gardeners formed from the produce show entered the [[Chelsea Flower Show]].  They won a [[silver gilt]] in the ''Best Courtyard Garden Award'' in two consecutive years, for gardens named "Calma" and "Time Lords".<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=153}}</ref>

Since 1957 there has been an annual performance of the York Nativity Play from the 15th century [[York Mystery Cycle]]. The play follows a script by [[E. Martin Browne]] with carols by [[William Byrd]], [[Johannes Eccard]], and [[Michael Praetorius]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Get Wokingham|2008}}</ref> The performances are at the Church of St Mary the Virgin in early December, and the actors are local people who have appeared in the play for many years.<ref>{{harvtxt|Newbury Theatre|2005}}</ref> In 1964, the play was recorded and broadcasted by the [[BBC Home Service]] under the title of ''Star Over Aldermaston''. One member of the production team was [[David Shute]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=31}}</ref>

Aldermaston was the original location of [[The Glade]] Festival. The 2007 event was jeopardised by torrential rains and flooding but cautiously went ahead.<ref name="Virtual Festivals 2007"/> In 2009, the festival was held near [[Winchester]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Rave Talk|2008}}</ref> Since 2006, the village has held a [[blues]] festival known as "Blues on the Meadow".<ref>{{harvtxt|Papworth|2010}}</ref>

The parish of Aldermaston forms a group with the local parishes of [[Wasing]] and [[Brimpton]]. The three share a monthly Parish Magazine featuring stories from churches, organisations, schools, businesses and various miscellany.<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2010a}}</ref>

==Transport==
[[File:Aldermaston railway station 2.JPG|thumb|alt=Photograph of a railway station plaform, showing the main two pairs of rails, a footbridge, and an old rusted siding|right|[[Aldermaston railway station]], looking to the west]]
[[Aldermaston railway station]] is in [[Aldermaston Wharf]],<ref>{{harvtxt|National Rail|2010a}}</ref> {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} from the village itself. The station is managed by [[National Rail]] and served by [[First Great Western]] services between {{stnlnk|Reading}} and {{stnlnk|Newbury}}.

The village is on the [[A340 road]], and has nearby access to the [[A4 road (England)|A4 road]] and the [[M4 motorway]]. [[Newbury Buses]] route 104 serves the village, with services terminating in Newbury, [[Calcot, Berkshire|Calcot]] and Reading.<ref>{{harvtxt|West Berkshire Council|2010c}}</ref> The 2005 Parish Plan identified a need for a [[relief road]] near the village. A report was presented in 2009 evaluating the problems caused by [[Heavy Goods Vehicle|HGV]] traffic through the village,<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2009|p=2}}</ref> and described solutions which included support from [[Newbury (UK Parliament constituency)|Newbury MP]] [[Richard Benyon]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Parish Council|2009|p=9}}</ref>

The nearest operating airstrip, [[Brimpton Airfield]], is less than {{convert|1|mi|km}} west of the village, within AWE's [[restricted airspace]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Brimpton Airfield|2009}}</ref> [[RAF Aldermaston]] ceased to operate as a civilian airport in 1950.<ref name="Timmins 2000 15"/>

The village is {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} south-east of the Reading Marine Company's headquarters on the [[Kennet and Avon Canal]],<ref>{{harvtxt|Reading Marine Company|2009}}</ref> which provides waterway links to London (via the Thames) and [[Bristol]] (via the [[River Avon (Bristol)|River Avon]]).<ref>{{harvtxt|Waterscape|2010b}}</ref>

==Education==
The parish of Aldermaston has two [[primary school]]s. Aldermaston Primary School is a [[state school|Local Authority-run]] [[Church of England school#United Kingdom|Church of England school]] in Wasing Lane and has about 150 pupils.<ref>{{harvtxt|DirectGov|2010a}}</ref> It was established in 1836<ref name="Scott 2007 10"/> and originally located in Church Road, moving to the present site in 1988.<ref>{{harvtxt|West Berkshire Council|2010d}}</ref> The school uses the names of the manor's squires in its [[house system]].<ref>{{harvtxt|West Berkshire Council|2010d}}</ref>

The Cedars is a [[private school]] opened in 1992 in the former buildings of the Church of England school.<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=109}}</ref> The school has approximately 40 pupils enrolled.<ref>{{harvtxt|DirectGov|2010b}}</ref>

Alder Bridge [[Steiner School]], although located in Aldermaston Wharf, is within the parish of Padworth.<ref>{{harvtxt|Newbury Weekly News|2008}}</ref> [[Padworth College]] is situated on the border of Aldermaston and Padworth parishes.

==Parish church==
{{main|Church of St Mary the Virgin, Aldermaston}}
[[File:StMarysAldermaston.jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph of a church with roughcast walls and square belltower.  A number of gravestones are visible in the foreground|[[Church of St Mary the Virgin, Aldermaston|Church of St Mary the Virgin]]]]
The [[Church of England parish church]] of [[Mary (mother of Jesus)|Saint Mary the Virgin]] and was built in the mid 12th century. The [[Norman architecture|Norman]] building was altered throughout the following millennium, particularly in 13th, 14th, 15th and 17th centuries.<ref name="pageditchfield5">{{harvtxt|Page|Ditchfield|1923|p=5}}</ref> The 12th-century building now comprises the current [[nave]], with additions seen in the Forster Chapel and [[chancel]] (13th century), the [[Steeple (architecture)|steeple]] (14th century), and vestry (17th century).<ref name="pageditchfield5" /> The 17th-century [[Jacobean era|Jacobean]] [[pulpit]] is an unusual [[heptagon]]al design.<ref name="Cox 1977 4"/> Various additions were made to the structure in the 14th and 15th centuries, primarily to the walls and [[ogee]] windows.<ref name="pageditchfield5" /> A [[Sun dial|scratch dial]] was added to the south-west [[buttress]] in the 14th century.<ref name="Cox 1977 4"/>

The church features architecture by [[Edward Doran Webb]]<ref name="pageditchfield5" /> and [[stained glass]] by [[Charles Eamer Kempe]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Timmins|2000|p=5}}</ref> The [[Church of St Mary the Virgin, Aldermaston#Forster Chapel|Forster Chapel]], a [[lady chapel]] added to the south face in the 13th century, contains the [[alabaster]] [[church monument|effigial monument]] of Sir George Forster and his wife Elizabeth which was built in 1530.<ref name="Reader's Digest Association 1990 18"/> Evidence suggests that the chapel may originally have been a [[chantry]] dedicated to [[St Nicholas]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Timmins|2000|p=4}}</ref> The roundel windows in the north wall date from the 13th century and are the oldest glass in Berkshire.<ref>{{harvtxt|Ford|2003}}</ref>

The tower has a [[Change ringing|peal]] of eight bells dating from 1681 to 1900. The current organ, which has 16 [[Organ stop|stops]], was installed in 1880.<ref name="NPOR">{{harvtxt|British Institute of Organ Studies|2008}}</ref>

Individuals buried in the churchyard include squires Charles Keyser (1847&ndash;1929) and Daniel Burr (c.1811&ndash;1885), schoolmaster John Stair (c.1745&ndash;1820), and [[Maria Hale]] (1791&ndash;1879).<ref name="Aldermaston Parish Council 2007 3" />

==Sport==
Aldermaston has a number of sports teams. The village [[cricket]] team, Aldermaston Village CC, play at nearby [[Wasing Park]].<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Village Cricket Club|2010a}}</ref> The club, which first played in 1786 as "The Gentlemen of Aldermaston", originally played at a pitch at Aldermaston Court.<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston Village Cricket Club|2010b}}</ref> The ground was lost when the airfield was built.  [[Sir William Mount, 2nd Baronet]], the grandfather of [[British Prime Minister]] [[David Cameron]], allowed a cricket pitch to be established on a portion of his Wasing estate.<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=156}}</ref> The original football club played next to the cricket pitch. The club's [[Kit (association football)|strip]] was sponsored by Mr. George L Heighton &ndash; the proprietor of the village shop.<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=55}}</ref>

Aldermaston Rugby Club and [[A.F.C. Aldermaston]] both play their home games at the Recreational Society at AWE.<ref>{{harvtxt|Aldermaston RFC|2007}}</ref> Tadley RFC is in the parish,<ref>{{harvtxt|Tadley RFC|2010}}</ref> about {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} from the village.

==Notable residents==
* [[Thomas Allibone]], Lord of the Manor (1953&ndash;1985)<ref name="Timmins 2000 15"/>
* [[Alan Caiger-Smith]], the studio potter, founded [[Aldermaston Pottery]]<ref>{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=9}}</ref>
* [[Duncan Grant]], painter, lived in the village with Paul Roche for the last few years of his life, and died in the village<ref name="Martin 2005 49">{{harvtxt|Martin|Braithwaite|Jeffcoate|Girling|2005|p=49}}</ref>
* [[Felix Pole]], Lord of the Manor (1939&ndash;1953)<ref name="Timmins 2000 12"/>
* [[Paul Roche]], poet, lived in the village<ref name="Martin 2005 49"/>

